WEBVTT

00:00:18.267 --> 00:00:23.100
-CLARKSON:  Tonight, Richard
spins off the track. Twice!

00:00:23.133 --> 00:00:26.033
-Jay Kay tries to get
to number one.

00:00:26.067 --> 00:00:29.300
And Germany or Britain,
which is best?

00:00:37.033 --> 00:00:40.367
Thank you. Hello!
Hello and welcome.

00:00:41.567 --> 00:00:43.400
Thanks very much. Now...

00:00:44.900 --> 00:00:48.267
Now, after our, uh,
our recent trip to Japan,

00:00:48.300 --> 00:00:50.967
where I raced
the bullet train,

00:00:51.000 --> 00:00:52.633
I stayed on for an extra day

00:00:52.667 --> 00:00:56.300
so I could drive
the incredible Nissan GT-R
around the track.

00:00:56.333 --> 00:00:59.233
Now, James, on the other hand,
he decided to stay on
for a little while

00:00:59.267 --> 00:01:01.867
because he wanted
to drive a car
which he claimed

00:01:01.900 --> 00:01:05.633
would be a lot more relevant
to the average
British motorist

00:01:05.667 --> 00:01:08.867
than a jumped-up
£50,000 Datsun.

00:01:14.300 --> 00:01:18.867
MAY:  Now, I'm fairly confident
you won't have seen
one of these before.

00:01:20.300 --> 00:01:21.967
Are you ready?

00:01:26.100 --> 00:01:28.067
It's called the Orochi,

00:01:28.067 --> 00:01:33.067
and it's looks are based
on a fish, a snake and
Pamela Anderson's mouth.

00:01:35.800 --> 00:01:37.500
I rather like it.

00:01:38.133 --> 00:01:40.367
It costs £44,000.

00:01:40.400 --> 00:01:44.133
It's made by a company
called Mitsuoka.

00:01:44.167 --> 00:01:46.100
You've probably
never heard of them either,

00:01:46.133 --> 00:01:49.200
but they are a proper
Japanese car maker.

00:01:49.233 --> 00:01:52.333
In fact, they're the tenth
biggest car maker
in the country,

00:01:52.367 --> 00:01:57.367
after Toyota, Nissan, Honda
and six others.

00:02:03.067 --> 00:02:07.700
Mitsuoka makes the chassis,
the body and the interior
all by itself,

00:02:07.733 --> 00:02:12.133
but the engine,
a 3.3-litre V6,
comes from Toyota.

00:02:17.633 --> 00:02:19.700
So, it looks
like a sports car,

00:02:19.733 --> 00:02:21.467
but is it any good as one?

00:02:21.500 --> 00:02:25.200
Well, it isn't very fast,
it doesn't make much noise

00:02:25.233 --> 00:02:28.900
and the ride
is surprisingly comfortable.

00:02:28.933 --> 00:02:31.067
By which I mean,
the ride is actually

00:02:31.067 --> 00:02:32.933
rather excellent
for a supercar,

00:02:32.967 --> 00:02:35.800
so, obviously,
I think it suits me
rather well.

00:02:35.833 --> 00:02:40.167
Although, Hammond and Clarkson
might like to
continue shopping around.

00:02:41.433 --> 00:02:43.167
But Mitsuoka
makes another car,

00:02:43.200 --> 00:02:46.467
which, on paper,
is even more up my street.

00:02:50.933 --> 00:02:54.333
Here it is,
and it's called the Galue.

00:02:54.367 --> 00:02:57.433
That foremost
social commentator,
Alan Partridge,

00:02:57.467 --> 00:03:01.600
once said that the Lexus
is Japan's Mercedes-Benz.

00:03:01.633 --> 00:03:06.200
In which case,
the Mitsuoka Galue could be,
but this is only a hunch,

00:03:06.933 --> 00:03:08.500
Japan's Rolls-Royce.

00:03:10.367 --> 00:03:13.767
But at a nice,
un-Rolls-Royce-ish price,

00:03:13.800 --> 00:03:17.400
because it costs
an agreeable £32,000.

00:03:18.333 --> 00:03:20.767
But looking like a Rolls-Royce
is one thing,

00:03:20.800 --> 00:03:25.233
feeling like a Rolls-Royce
is something
completely different.

00:03:25.267 --> 00:03:27.500
So, to find out
whether it does or not,

00:03:27.533 --> 00:03:32.133
the producers have arranged
for me to do a spot
of VIP chauffeuring.

00:03:32.900 --> 00:03:34.200
Not him.

00:03:35.367 --> 00:03:37.400
Them.

00:03:37.433 --> 00:03:41.967
Yes, the local sumo wrestler
and his manager
need taking to a tournament.

00:03:47.167 --> 00:03:49.167
That's exhausted my Japanese.

00:03:50.367 --> 00:03:53.967
Right, back to
the Japanese Rolls-Royce.

00:03:54.067 --> 00:03:56.700
Inside the Galue,
Mitsuoka has recreated

00:03:56.733 --> 00:04:02.067
the ambience of a proper,
old school,
British luxury car.

00:04:02.100 --> 00:04:03.733
So, there's some wood-ish.

00:04:03.767 --> 00:04:05.700
There's plush leather seats.

00:04:05.733 --> 00:04:09.067
But look at this,
this clock is exactly,

00:04:09.067 --> 00:04:12.367
roughly like the one
on the new
Rolls-Royce Phantom.

00:04:12.400 --> 00:04:16.600
It's like one of those
fake expensive watches
you get in Thailand.

00:04:16.633 --> 00:04:19.533
Only a real expert
can tell the difference.

00:04:19.567 --> 00:04:23.567
I am a Rolls-Royce expert,
and I was completely taken in.

00:04:24.600 --> 00:04:26.200
Actually, I didn't mean that.

00:04:26.233 --> 00:04:29.200
What I meant to say was,
"It's an utterly
shameless rip-off,

00:04:29.233 --> 00:04:32.067
"and I can't believe
they're getting away with it."

00:04:32.067 --> 00:04:36.167
So, what about the performance
from the 3.5-litre V6?

00:04:36.200 --> 00:04:39.333
Is that the genuine article?

00:04:39.367 --> 00:04:42.467
A Rolls-Royce must be able
to whoosh away
from a stand still.

00:04:42.500 --> 00:04:47.267
It can go quite quickly,
but it must never feel urgent,
it must swell very gently,

00:04:47.300 --> 00:04:50.867
it must be an orchestral,
sort of, performance.

00:04:52.500 --> 00:04:54.467
Which that isn't. Sorry.

00:04:55.433 --> 00:04:57.767
Next, handling.

00:04:57.800 --> 00:05:02.067
A Rolls-Royce should
never allow its driver
to corner too vigourously

00:05:02.067 --> 00:05:03.333
because that would
be bad form.

00:05:03.367 --> 00:05:05.733
It must encourage you
to rein things back.

00:05:08.267 --> 00:05:10.300
Clearly, it's not quite right
in that respect.

00:05:10.333 --> 00:05:13.067
Very sorry. Very sorry.

00:05:14.933 --> 00:05:18.500
I cracked on with the job
of delivering my VIPs.

00:05:19.333 --> 00:05:20.500
Happy?

00:05:23.567 --> 00:05:26.200
Very close to the destination.

00:05:33.600 --> 00:05:35.200
What? Was that it?

00:05:35.233 --> 00:05:37.800
-Oh.

00:05:52.333 --> 00:05:55.100
I think they were
completely fooled.

00:05:59.833 --> 00:06:02.067
As some of you
may have found out last week,

00:06:02.067 --> 00:06:04.400
I have got an old Rolls,
and let me tell you,

00:06:04.433 --> 00:06:07.367
the Galue isn't even
on the same planet.

00:06:07.400 --> 00:06:11.067
But you know what,
this car does make me smile.

00:06:12.700 --> 00:06:18.300
It's not taking itself
too seriously.
It's just a bit of fun.

00:06:18.333 --> 00:06:21.300
It's a bit like
one of those tribute bands.

00:06:21.333 --> 00:06:26.100
Bjorn Again,
Letz Zep, the Strolling Bones.

00:06:26.133 --> 00:06:29.467
Like those bands,
it knows it's not
the real thing,

00:06:29.500 --> 00:06:34.567
but more importantly,
it knows you know
it's not the real thing.

00:06:34.600 --> 00:06:38.133
And anyway,
at the end of the evening,
you're still just as drunk,

00:06:38.167 --> 00:06:39.867
and you've still
had a great time,

00:06:39.900 --> 00:06:42.067
but it only cost you a fiver.

00:06:51.200 --> 00:06:54.733
Is that car
going to be sold
in the UK?

00:06:54.767 --> 00:06:56.833
-No.
-Good. Richard?

00:06:56.867 --> 00:06:59.700
Yes. Now, KTM are
an Austrian bike manufacturer,

00:06:59.733 --> 00:07:02.167
and they make things
like this, the Duke,
and it's great.

00:07:02.200 --> 00:07:05.300
But now they've decided
to have a go at a car,
and here it is.

00:07:05.333 --> 00:07:07.100
It's called the X-Bow.

00:07:07.133 --> 00:07:11.067
Now, the body's
made of plastic panels,
just like it is on the bike.

00:07:11.100 --> 00:07:13.433
You can see all the innards,
like you can on the bike,

00:07:13.467 --> 00:07:16.833
and you have to wear
a crash helmet to drive it,
like you do on the bike.

00:07:16.867 --> 00:07:19.067
It really is a stripped-out
track car.

00:07:19.067 --> 00:07:21.067
All you get is a seat,
a steering wheel

00:07:21.067 --> 00:07:22.767
and a two-litre
turbo-charged Audi engine

00:07:22.800 --> 00:07:26.600
that's enough to take it
to 60 miles an hour
in under four seconds.

00:07:26.633 --> 00:07:29.233
Apparently, KTM say
it is quite a handful,

00:07:29.267 --> 00:07:33.400
and as a result,
they won't sell it to drivers
under 24 years old.

00:07:33.433 --> 00:07:37.333
Just one thing,
Lewis Hamilton.
He's 23!

00:07:39.067 --> 00:07:43.067
Now, the thing about that
is it costs £43,000,

00:07:43.100 --> 00:07:44.233
which seems
like a hell of a lot

00:07:44.267 --> 00:07:46.800
for a motorcycle
with two extra wheels.

00:07:46.833 --> 00:07:48.600
-No, it isn't.
-Well, it is.

00:07:48.633 --> 00:07:50.600
It isn't. You could drive
that thing through...
What's it's called?

00:07:50.633 --> 00:07:52.067
-Oxbow? Something rather.
-Cross.

00:07:52.067 --> 00:07:54.367
You could drive that
through a light shower

00:07:54.400 --> 00:07:56.300
and you could come out
on the other side

00:07:56.333 --> 00:07:59.500
without your internal organs
being transplanted
into someone else.

00:07:59.533 --> 00:08:01.133
You don't get bikes...

00:08:01.167 --> 00:08:03.433
No, I'll tell you,
you two have to live
in fear and dread, okay,

00:08:03.467 --> 00:08:07.067
that you're gonna
go through the pearly gates
with your ripped leathers on,

00:08:07.067 --> 00:08:11.867
knowing full well
that I'm back on Earth,
as a car driver,

00:08:12.467 --> 00:08:14.067
with your liver.

00:08:15.533 --> 00:08:16.900
And don't think I'm going
to do anything useful with it

00:08:16.933 --> 00:08:18.567
because I'm just going
to make it into a hat.

00:08:20.100 --> 00:08:21.967
MAY: I actually carry
a card that says,

00:08:22.067 --> 00:08:27.900
"I do not wish to help
Jeremy Clarkson be amusing
in the event of my death."

00:08:27.933 --> 00:08:30.067
-Fair enough.
-Yes, now, every year,

00:08:30.067 --> 00:08:32.200
the Scouts
make a series of awards,

00:08:32.233 --> 00:08:34.367
uh, which are relevant
to them.

00:08:34.400 --> 00:08:36.433
Uh, I've got the list here.
They're very prestigious.

00:08:36.467 --> 00:08:38.167
They've just announced
this year's winners.

00:08:38.200 --> 00:08:40.800
Previous winners have included
Charley Boorman
and Ewan McGregor.

00:08:40.833 --> 00:08:42.133
They won
best navigation award.

00:08:42.167 --> 00:08:43.867
Jamie Oliver
won the healthy eating award.

00:08:43.900 --> 00:08:46.567
Yeah. Now, Ray Mears,
it has to be said,
has not won the award

00:08:46.600 --> 00:08:49.533
for services of wearing shorts
when you're a grown man.

00:08:50.967 --> 00:08:53.833
However,
their award,
this year,

00:08:53.867 --> 00:08:57.133
for services to instruction

00:08:57.167 --> 00:09:00.433
-has gone to The Stig.
-HAMMOND: Yeah!

00:09:05.600 --> 00:09:08.067
However, there's a problem,
a really big problem.

00:09:08.100 --> 00:09:11.500
They came down earlier
to give him his badge,

00:09:12.933 --> 00:09:14.333
and he attacked them.

00:09:16.100 --> 00:09:19.100
We've actually
got some footage
of it here, seriously.

00:09:19.133 --> 00:09:21.333
-CLARKSON: Look.

00:09:21.367 --> 00:09:24.400
Look, he's trying to stamp
on his badge, he hates it.

00:09:24.433 --> 00:09:28.733
And they took him down.
They actually took
The Stig down, two Scouts.

00:09:30.667 --> 00:09:32.067
It's awkward, that.

00:09:32.067 --> 00:09:35.100
It turns out
he's terrified
of Scouts, yeah.

00:09:35.133 --> 00:09:37.600
We think, um, he might
have been a Girl Guide.

00:09:39.067 --> 00:09:40.800
Okay, now, bad news.

00:09:40.833 --> 00:09:45.067
This week, James popped
around to see me, okay,
down at my local pub,

00:09:45.067 --> 00:09:49.267
parked his motorcycle,
outside, not illegally...

00:09:49.300 --> 00:09:51.600
-No, very considerately.
-No, it was illegal.

00:09:51.633 --> 00:09:54.400
That's right,
it was illegally parked,
but not inconsiderate.

00:09:54.433 --> 00:09:55.767
Yeah, exactly.

00:09:55.800 --> 00:09:58.333
Fined £120.

00:09:58.367 --> 00:10:01.300
120 quid. Now,
here's the thing, all right,

00:10:01.333 --> 00:10:06.400
both of us,
in the not too distant past,
have had televisions stolen.

00:10:06.433 --> 00:10:08.100
So, how come
they've got the man power

00:10:08.133 --> 00:10:10.833
to find your slightly
illegally parked motorcycle

00:10:10.867 --> 00:10:13.367
when they say
that they can't find
our televisions?

00:10:13.400 --> 00:10:15.067
I know. I don't understand it.
Because I rang up the woman

00:10:15.100 --> 00:10:18.533
-on the, uh, parking ticket
hotline enquiry hotline.
-Mmm.

00:10:18.567 --> 00:10:20.433
And I said to her,
"Have you found
my television?"

00:10:20.467 --> 00:10:23.700
-She had no idea
what I was talking about.

00:10:23.733 --> 00:10:26.833
I think that if you've
had something stolen
in your life...

00:10:26.867 --> 00:10:29.633
How many people here
have had something stolen?
The lawnmower...

00:10:29.667 --> 00:10:31.533
Right. Nearly everybody.

00:10:31.567 --> 00:10:35.667
It should be illegal
for the police to do you
for a trivial motoring offence

00:10:35.700 --> 00:10:38.067
until they've returned
whatever it is
you've had stolen!

00:10:38.100 --> 00:10:39.767
-Yes!

00:10:39.800 --> 00:10:41.400
-Does anybody here think...
Well, there we go.
-MAY: Yes, I do.

00:10:43.033 --> 00:10:46.800
-I think you're right there.
-Seriously...

00:10:46.833 --> 00:10:51.433
If you're watching this,
Mr Brown, that's 100% of
British people agree with me.

00:10:52.667 --> 00:10:54.433
-Hey, great news!
-What?

00:10:54.467 --> 00:10:57.733
I've been sent
more information
on the Dacia Sandero.

00:10:57.767 --> 00:11:00.333
-CLARKSON: Excellent!
-I've got a question
I want to ask.

00:11:00.367 --> 00:11:04.467
-CLARKSON: What?
-What if this turns out
to be really good?

00:11:04.500 --> 00:11:06.300
CLARKSON: Well, it won't.
HAMMOND: No,
but what if it does?

00:11:06.333 --> 00:11:09.067
-Well, it won't, will it?
-Well, it's the new
Chevy Camaro.

00:11:09.100 --> 00:11:11.333
And, um, they're really
thought about it.
It looks brilliant.

00:11:11.367 --> 00:11:13.067
And obviously
it's got a 6.2-litre V8,

00:11:13.067 --> 00:11:15.667
and they've given it
independent suspension
all round.

00:11:15.700 --> 00:11:18.433
-Wow!

00:11:18.467 --> 00:11:20.133
Independent!

00:11:20.167 --> 00:11:21.633
-HAMMOND: Yeah.
-So, they've looked at a car
and they thought,

00:11:21.667 --> 00:11:23.700
"It's got four
separate wheels.

00:11:23.733 --> 00:11:26.500
"Maybe... What if
we treated them all
sort of separate?"

00:11:26.533 --> 00:11:29.600
Yeah, like they've been
doing in Europe for 100 years?

00:11:29.633 --> 00:11:31.067
-I still think,

00:11:31.067 --> 00:11:33.600
what if that... Look at that!
Turns out to be good?

00:11:33.633 --> 00:11:35.233
-I mean, we don't know yet!
-CLARKSON: Richard! Richard,

00:11:35.267 --> 00:11:38.100
the Americans are
good at herding bison.

00:11:38.133 --> 00:11:40.067
-The end.

00:11:40.100 --> 00:11:42.567
I still maintain
it might turn out to be good,
then we'll all want one.

00:11:42.600 --> 00:11:45.667
Okay, what is this underneath?
Underneath, this is
a Vauxhall VXR, isn't it?

00:11:45.700 --> 00:11:47.433
-HAMMOND: Yeah.
-CLARKSON: Which is
actually a Holden.

00:11:47.467 --> 00:11:49.267
So what the Americans
have done, yeah,
is they've gone,

00:11:49.300 --> 00:11:52.533
"We need some
sophistication here.
We'll call the Australians."

00:11:54.300 --> 00:11:57.067
That is like saying,
"I want some style
for my wedding,

00:11:57.100 --> 00:11:59.067
"I'll get seven
crates of lager."

00:12:01.133 --> 00:12:03.567
Do you know, you're the sort
of person I could show you
a picture of Paris Hilton

00:12:03.600 --> 00:12:06.067
and you'd say,
"What if she turns out
to be intelligent?"

00:12:06.100 --> 00:12:09.067
-But what if she did?
What if she did?

00:12:09.067 --> 00:12:11.300
All right.
That's enough news.

00:12:11.333 --> 00:12:13.133
So, now, Mazda.

00:12:13.167 --> 00:12:15.900
Over the years,
they've built up
a fearsome reputation

00:12:15.933 --> 00:12:17.600
for making
very sensible small cars

00:12:17.633 --> 00:12:22.067
and the worst
television commercials
in all of human history.

00:12:22.100 --> 00:12:24.533
This, however,
is their latest creation.

00:12:24.567 --> 00:12:26.367
Plainly, they wanted
to give it a name

00:12:26.400 --> 00:12:30.700
which conjured up an image
of aggression and anger,

00:12:30.733 --> 00:12:32.133
but unfortunately,
the job of naming it

00:12:32.167 --> 00:12:33.800
was given to somebody
from Birmingham,

00:12:33.833 --> 00:12:36.967
so, it's ended up
being called the Furai.

00:12:37.067 --> 00:12:39.967
The chassis is from
an American Le Mans racer,

00:12:40.067 --> 00:12:42.267
which is the same as
a European Le Mans racer,

00:12:42.300 --> 00:12:44.300
-only fatter.

00:12:44.333 --> 00:12:49.833
Body, that was clearly
designed by someone
with a Batman fixation.

00:12:49.867 --> 00:12:52.500
Uh... I think it looks
absolutely brilliant actually,

00:12:52.533 --> 00:12:54.533
although if you take it
to a film premiere,

00:12:54.567 --> 00:12:57.867
-it'll probably take a swing
at its sister.

00:12:57.900 --> 00:12:59.467
Allegedly, that is, of course.

00:12:59.500 --> 00:13:05.433
Um, the engine, Wankel,
1.9-litre,
460 brake horsepower,

00:13:05.467 --> 00:13:07.967
2.6 miles to the gallon.

00:13:08.633 --> 00:13:11.567
And, annoyingly, broken.

00:13:11.600 --> 00:13:13.833
Which means
we can't put it round
our test track.

00:13:13.867 --> 00:13:18.167
So, instead, I'm going
to answer a question that,
literally, a viewer has asked.

00:13:18.200 --> 00:13:20.667
And I have their letter here.
It says,

00:13:20.700 --> 00:13:22.867
"Dear so called  Top Gear,

00:13:22.900 --> 00:13:26.733
"I'm aware that there are many
elegant and dramatic supercars
that I could buy..."

00:13:26.767 --> 00:13:28.300
Well, yeah, things like these.

00:13:28.333 --> 00:13:31.300
"...But as I'm the victim
of a botched eye operation,

00:13:31.333 --> 00:13:36.067
"what I want is a supercar
that is catastrophically ugly.
Can you help?"

00:13:36.800 --> 00:13:38.433
Yes, I think I can.

00:13:41.167 --> 00:13:43.600
HAMMOND:
This could be the answer
to your problems.

00:13:43.633 --> 00:13:46.067
It's a new supercar
from Germany,

00:13:46.067 --> 00:13:49.067
and, well,
it's not exactly a looker.

00:13:50.900 --> 00:13:54.333
Let me put it this way.
When Jeremy did the Alfa 8C...

00:13:56.733 --> 00:13:58.800
...the camera crew found there
wasn't a single angle

00:13:58.833 --> 00:14:01.500
that didn't make
the car look brilliant.

00:14:01.533 --> 00:14:04.233
This is the exact opposite.

00:14:05.400 --> 00:14:07.733
No. No.

00:14:07.767 --> 00:14:09.900
-Really, no.

00:14:12.067 --> 00:14:14.567
And then there's the problem
of the name.

00:14:15.333 --> 00:14:17.233
Does it have
one of those sexy ones,

00:14:17.267 --> 00:14:19.133
like all the sexiest
cars have,

00:14:19.167 --> 00:14:22.167
you know,
Vanquish, Viper, Raptor?

00:14:22.200 --> 00:14:25.100
No. It's called a Gumpert.

00:14:26.733 --> 00:14:29.800
-So, it's got looks
only a mother could love

00:14:29.833 --> 00:14:32.200
and a name
like a Northern comedian.

00:14:33.300 --> 00:14:35.700
-And for the privilege
of driving it,

00:14:35.733 --> 00:14:39.367
you'll need £250,000.

00:14:39.400 --> 00:14:43.900
This does beg the question,
what do you get
for your money?

00:14:43.933 --> 00:14:48.067
Certainly, you're not
buying a wondrous
Zonda-esque interior.

00:14:48.067 --> 00:14:51.500
It's just a random collection
of bits from Audi.

00:14:51.533 --> 00:14:54.567
Maybe then, it has
some amazing options.

00:14:56.733 --> 00:15:01.900
Well, yes, but don't
go looking for night-vision
or a bathroom.

00:15:03.400 --> 00:15:06.867
And this,
the rear-view camera,
doesn't count.

00:15:06.900 --> 00:15:09.133
That's a necessity.
There's no back window.

00:15:11.567 --> 00:15:16.200
Options on the Gumpert
are things like this,
the traction control.

00:15:18.100 --> 00:15:20.133
Now, lots of cars
have traction control,

00:15:20.167 --> 00:15:23.833
but the Gumpert's
is really quite anorak-ey.

00:15:23.867 --> 00:15:25.567
It's not a button,
it's a knob.

00:15:25.600 --> 00:15:27.567
You can adjust it
so you can be precise.

00:15:27.600 --> 00:15:30.900
So, Hammerhead coming up.
I know this corner.

00:15:30.933 --> 00:15:32.633
17%, I think.

00:15:39.133 --> 00:15:41.933
-Yeah, that... That...

00:15:42.700 --> 00:15:44.633
But worry not.

00:15:44.667 --> 00:15:48.167
If that doesn't work out,
there are whole load of
other things you can adjust.

00:15:48.200 --> 00:15:52.467
You can change the camber,
the ride height,
the spring tension,

00:15:52.500 --> 00:15:55.467
the damper,
bump and rebound
and the anti-roll bar.

00:15:57.367 --> 00:16:02.067
Oh, yeah! There you are,
Monte Carlo, Claudia Schiffer,
in your supercar,

00:16:02.100 --> 00:16:04.067
"Please can we go
to the party now?"

00:16:04.100 --> 00:16:06.433
"Oh, no, no, hold on.
A lot of corners.

00:16:06.467 --> 00:16:08.933
"I'm gonna dial in
some extra camber."

00:16:10.533 --> 00:16:13.067
With the camber adjusted,
I went for...

00:16:13.067 --> 00:16:16.067
-Oh, bugger.

00:16:17.633 --> 00:16:20.700
You see,
I think some of those settings
are not an option.

00:16:20.733 --> 00:16:22.267
Just leave them alone!

00:16:24.700 --> 00:16:27.400
-I've had this experience
with one of my bikes.

00:16:27.433 --> 00:16:31.500
All you ever do
is make things worse.

00:16:31.533 --> 00:16:36.400
There is one option
this car doesn't have,
and it's one I quite like.

00:16:36.433 --> 00:16:39.800
The option to move your seat
backwards and forwards.

00:16:39.833 --> 00:16:42.367
Now, that's because
the Gumpert people got fed up

00:16:42.400 --> 00:16:45.133
with drivers
moving their seats around

00:16:45.167 --> 00:16:47.733
and messing up their perfect
weight distribution.

00:16:50.400 --> 00:16:53.067
So, minging looks,
seats you can't move

00:16:53.067 --> 00:16:56.267
and gizmos only Lewis Hamilton
can make sense of.

00:16:56.300 --> 00:16:57.933
I think you're getting
the picture by now

00:16:57.967 --> 00:17:01.733
that this is
no Riviera cruiser.

00:17:01.767 --> 00:17:06.400
Their fastest version,
the Apollo Race,
has 800 brake horsepower,

00:17:06.433 --> 00:17:08.300
but if you've just passed
your driving test,

00:17:08.333 --> 00:17:13.300
they do do, what they call
"an entry-level version",
650 brake horsepower.

00:17:13.800 --> 00:17:15.433
This is the mid-range.

00:17:15.467 --> 00:17:19.967
I suppose they'd call it
"the Popular Plus",
700 brake horsepower.

00:17:21.733 --> 00:17:24.667
-And this is where
it all starts to come good

00:17:24.700 --> 00:17:28.767
because whichever
Gumpert you choose,
it's going to be fast.

00:17:36.533 --> 00:17:37.567
Gods!

00:17:41.600 --> 00:17:43.300
This is just something else!

00:17:45.767 --> 00:17:48.267
The engine
is Audi's 4.2-litre V8,

00:17:48.300 --> 00:17:50.067
but with added
twin turbos,

00:17:50.100 --> 00:17:52.933
all wrapped up
in featherweight carbon fibre.

00:17:54.833 --> 00:17:57.400
Naught to 60, three seconds.

00:17:57.433 --> 00:18:01.333
Top speed, 224 miles an hour.

00:18:01.367 --> 00:18:03.533
So, let's see
how much of that we can get

00:18:03.567 --> 00:18:05.267
on our modest runway.

00:18:08.700 --> 00:18:11.933
That's 200 kilometres an hour.
That's 120 miles an hour.

00:18:15.233 --> 00:18:19.267
That's 280 kilometres an hour,
which is very fast.

00:18:21.933 --> 00:18:24.067
300 kilometres an hour.

00:18:24.067 --> 00:18:27.067
I'm gonna start
breaking, I think.

00:18:27.067 --> 00:18:31.333
That's 186 miles an hour
in 1.7 miles.

00:18:34.067 --> 00:18:36.067
And when you get to a corner,

00:18:36.067 --> 00:18:39.933
just as long as you've not
been fiddling with anything,
it is brilliant.

00:18:45.600 --> 00:18:46.900
The grip!

00:18:48.067 --> 00:18:50.167
My eyes are a foot
that side of my head!

00:18:53.067 --> 00:18:54.967
Suddenly you realise
why this thing

00:18:55.067 --> 00:18:58.133
looks like a boil
on the buttock of a baboon.

00:18:58.167 --> 00:19:03.067
It's got downforce,
that's what all those holes,
fins and grills are for.

00:19:12.667 --> 00:19:17.900
If you want a supercar
you can park with pride in
Monte Carlo's Casino Square,

00:19:17.933 --> 00:19:20.667
this probably isn't for you.

00:19:20.700 --> 00:19:24.867
There are many other cars
that will do that job
much better.

00:19:24.900 --> 00:19:27.767
But the Gumpert guys,
in their little
German factory,

00:19:27.800 --> 00:19:29.967
have gone down another path.

00:19:30.067 --> 00:19:31.700
Hardcore Street.

00:19:33.433 --> 00:19:36.767
And I do believe
that on this track,
old Quasimodo here

00:19:37.767 --> 00:19:40.067
could destroy
every supercar alive.

00:19:54.967 --> 00:19:56.800
CLARKSON: Are you...

00:19:56.833 --> 00:19:59.367
Are you really suggesting
this is gonna be quicker
round the track

00:19:59.400 --> 00:20:01.567
than, sort of, lots
of the really fast cars?

00:20:01.600 --> 00:20:03.167
It is unbelievably quick.

00:20:03.200 --> 00:20:05.000
But I tell you,
the amazing thing
about this car.

00:20:05.033 --> 00:20:07.033
You know in the film
I said it generates downforce

00:20:07.067 --> 00:20:08.633
-to stick it to the road?
-Mmm.

00:20:08.667 --> 00:20:10.700
Well, Gumpert say
it generates so much

00:20:10.733 --> 00:20:12.933
that it could
drive upside down

00:20:12.967 --> 00:20:14.367
and still stick to the roof...

00:20:14.400 --> 00:20:16.200
Oh, you don't fall
for that old chestnut!

00:20:16.233 --> 00:20:19.400
Every Formula One team
says, "Oh, you could drive
our cars upside down."

00:20:19.433 --> 00:20:23.033
The only reason they say that
is because they know
we can't prove them wrong.

00:20:23.067 --> 00:20:25.367
Yeah, but Gumpert
are going to prove it.

00:20:25.400 --> 00:20:27.900
They've built an engine
that will work upside down.

00:20:27.933 --> 00:20:31.100
-Yeah, and the tunnel?
-And they found a tunnel
they can do it in.

00:20:31.133 --> 00:20:33.467
Okay, so how fast
do you have to drive

00:20:33.500 --> 00:20:36.700
to generate enough downforce
or upforce to stick it?

00:20:36.733 --> 00:20:37.867
190 miles an hour.

00:20:37.900 --> 00:20:39.167
Right. So, they're gonna
get someone to drive

00:20:39.200 --> 00:20:41.333
at 190 miles an hour
down the roof of a tunnel,

00:20:41.367 --> 00:20:43.633
swerving between
all the signposts,

00:20:43.667 --> 00:20:45.300
-fans and lights!

00:20:45.333 --> 00:20:47.667
You see, that's the thing.
They found the tunnel
to do it in,

00:20:47.700 --> 00:20:50.867
but they've not yet found
anyone stupid enough
to drive it.

00:20:52.667 --> 00:20:54.233
Well, this is the last show.

00:20:55.233 --> 00:20:58.133
No, I can't.
No, I can't.

00:20:58.167 --> 00:20:59.267
-Why not?
-I'm busy.

00:20:59.300 --> 00:21:01.433
I'm busy.
I'm painting...my horse.

00:21:01.467 --> 00:21:03.500
-I just can't do it.

00:21:03.533 --> 00:21:04.933
Anyway, we must now find out

00:21:04.967 --> 00:21:06.700
how fast it goes
round our track,

00:21:06.733 --> 00:21:10.400
which means
we must put it in the hands
of our tame racing driver.

00:21:10.433 --> 00:21:14.533
Some say it's impossible
for him to wear socks.

00:21:14.567 --> 00:21:20.333
-And he can open a beer bottle
with his testes.

00:21:20.367 --> 00:21:23.933
All we know is
he's called The Stig.

00:21:23.967 --> 00:21:26.133
-HAMMOND:  And he's off,
not a scorching start.

00:21:26.167 --> 00:21:30.567
Stig just carefully
metering out the power,
of which there is a lot.

00:21:30.600 --> 00:21:32.533
Up to the first corner now,

00:21:32.567 --> 00:21:34.667
hopefully he's gonna
be going faster to
get that downforce working.

00:21:34.700 --> 00:21:37.467
-And that is neat,
I've got high hopes for this.

00:21:37.500 --> 00:21:39.367
Really, I have.

00:21:44.633 --> 00:21:47.067
Yeah, Stig still apparently
touched by Elton John.

00:21:47.100 --> 00:21:48.567
Maybe he actually enjoys it.

00:21:48.600 --> 00:21:51.367
That is fantastically
controlled through Chicago.

00:21:52.533 --> 00:21:54.600
Hammerhead now, slower corner.

00:21:54.633 --> 00:21:57.433
Could be in trouble
if the fancy aerodynamics
can't do their stuff there.

00:21:57.467 --> 00:21:59.167
Not a bit of it though.

00:21:59.200 --> 00:22:01.433
It's so undramatic
and I suspect that could
be this car's secret.

00:22:04.800 --> 00:22:09.067
Right, the follow-through,
really pin it open now,
will he have to lift?

00:22:09.100 --> 00:22:12.267
Not likely! You can almost
see it being pressed
into the tarmac,

00:22:12.300 --> 00:22:15.267
it's so flat
through the corners
like a racing car.

00:22:15.300 --> 00:22:17.067
Up to Gambon.

00:22:17.100 --> 00:22:19.700
Finally biting back,
but Stig's on it
and across the line.

00:22:24.667 --> 00:22:26.733
Hang on a minute.
Hang on. Wait!

00:22:26.767 --> 00:22:31.100
If you're right, it's gonna be
up with, what, the Zonda,
the Koenigsegg, the Ascari...

00:22:31.133 --> 00:22:35.233
Yep, stuff at the top.
Ascari did it in 1.17.3.

00:22:35.267 --> 00:22:41.333
So, the Gumbert
did it in it 1.17.1!

00:22:41.367 --> 00:22:43.600
-It is the fastest!

00:22:46.567 --> 00:22:51.167
-It beat Ascari!
-Fastest ever
around our track.

00:22:51.200 --> 00:22:54.400
That really is incredible
because that is the first car

00:22:54.433 --> 00:22:56.533
Hammond has driven
round our circuit,

00:22:56.567 --> 00:22:59.433
or driven on our circuit,
I should say,
this year, isn't it?

00:22:59.467 --> 00:23:02.400
-Yeah.
-And it's gone to the top
of the leaderboard...

00:23:02.433 --> 00:23:05.333
-...which he can't reach.

00:23:05.367 --> 00:23:07.933
No, no, no. I can, I can!
I just need a run up.

00:23:07.967 --> 00:23:10.433
This is going
to be undignified.

00:23:12.067 --> 00:23:14.533
-It's not worked.

00:23:14.567 --> 00:23:16.067
It's on!

00:23:22.967 --> 00:23:25.300
Okay, that's one, um...

00:23:25.333 --> 00:23:28.733
-That's one lap record
smashed, quite literally.

00:23:28.767 --> 00:23:31.133
Now, let's see
if we can't deal
with another one.

00:23:31.167 --> 00:23:35.600
This is a list of the stars
who've driven
our reasonably priced car

00:23:35.633 --> 00:23:39.933
and Simon Cowell has now
been at the top for the last
two series, okay,

00:23:39.967 --> 00:23:42.867
which we think is long enough.

00:23:42.900 --> 00:23:46.067
So what we've done
is we went back
and looked at all the people

00:23:46.067 --> 00:23:48.500
who drove our old
reasonably priced car,

00:23:48.533 --> 00:23:52.333
found the biggest petrol head
and invited him back.

00:23:52.367 --> 00:23:55.600
Ladies and gentlemen,
would you please
welcome Jay Kay!

00:23:58.967 --> 00:24:01.433
Thank you very much.
Thank you very much.

00:24:01.467 --> 00:24:04.533
-How are you? Have a seat.

00:24:04.567 --> 00:24:06.100
Thank you.

00:24:10.567 --> 00:24:13.833
-You have been
nagging to be here.

00:24:13.867 --> 00:24:15.700
Honestly, there hasn't
been a week go by...

00:24:15.733 --> 00:24:17.067
How long is it
since you were here?

00:24:17.067 --> 00:24:19.600
I was here
on the first series,

00:24:19.633 --> 00:24:21.133
I think I was the second guy.

00:24:21.167 --> 00:24:23.367
-You were the second
guest ever.
-Second guest ever.

00:24:23.400 --> 00:24:25.400
No, there hasn't
been a week really,

00:24:25.433 --> 00:24:28.800
I think I'm honest,
gone by since then to now

00:24:28.833 --> 00:24:30.100
when you haven't been
on the phone going,

00:24:30.133 --> 00:24:31.767
"Can I come back?
Can I come back?"

00:24:31.800 --> 00:24:35.367
Yeah, I did...
I have to say I felt
left out, I felt lonely,

00:24:35.400 --> 00:24:38.200
I sat in my kitchen
watching it thinking,

00:24:38.233 --> 00:24:40.267
-"When will I come back?
-You were always on the...

00:24:40.300 --> 00:24:44.233
"When will I beat the man
with the codpiece?"

00:24:44.267 --> 00:24:45.867
-Oh, Simon?
-Codpiece Cowell!

00:24:45.900 --> 00:24:48.800
Codpiece Cowell!
Actually, I've just
remembered something,

00:24:48.833 --> 00:24:50.900
what was it you said
to the researcher?

00:24:50.933 --> 00:24:52.367
When we rang up and said,
"Can you come back?"

00:24:52.400 --> 00:24:54.267
I said,
"I'm down here for war."

00:24:54.300 --> 00:24:57.200
- Yes! He did!
-I'm down here for war!

00:24:57.233 --> 00:24:59.200
-It's actually...
-I'm not here to muck about,

00:24:59.233 --> 00:25:02.600
I'm not here to be 13th,
I'm not here
to beat James Blunt,

00:25:02.633 --> 00:25:06.067
-I'm here to be
on the top now.

00:25:06.067 --> 00:25:08.067
-You know...
-So first or nothing else
will do?

00:25:08.100 --> 00:25:10.600
I'm not here
to beat James Blunt's
album sales either.

00:25:10.633 --> 00:25:14.200
-No, because how many
have you sold in total? 25...
-25 million or something.

00:25:14.233 --> 00:25:16.700
25 million and you
can't read music.

00:25:16.733 --> 00:25:19.233
-Thank you, everybody.

00:25:19.267 --> 00:25:21.067
Thank you.

00:25:21.067 --> 00:25:22.933
-Somebody else.

00:25:22.967 --> 00:25:24.067
That is a lot.

00:25:24.067 --> 00:25:26.867
That is a lot of albums.

00:25:26.900 --> 00:25:30.800
Uh, now, I won't bother going
through the list of everything
you've got

00:25:30.833 --> 00:25:32.267
because the programme
is only an hour long.

00:25:32.300 --> 00:25:34.200
But how many cars
have you got these days?

00:25:34.233 --> 00:25:38.833
Oh, there are 37 vehicles,
including motorbikes,
that's including motorbikes,

00:25:38.867 --> 00:25:41.133
and staff cars
because people...

00:25:41.167 --> 00:25:43.600
-Staff? Staff cars!
-Staff cars!

00:25:43.633 --> 00:25:47.233
No, no, they don't
have little flags
and swastikas on!

00:25:49.200 --> 00:25:51.967
Or, sort of, you know,
two wheels at the front
and a half track at the back.

00:25:52.067 --> 00:25:53.667
-At the back, yes.

00:25:53.700 --> 00:25:55.133
Now, since you were last here,

00:25:55.167 --> 00:25:56.667
-what have been
the main changes?
-Yeah.

00:25:56.700 --> 00:25:58.500
-What's...
-Well, the main stuff

00:25:58.533 --> 00:26:00.667
is that I've got
into Porsches,

00:26:00.700 --> 00:26:02.600
for some unknown reason.

00:26:02.633 --> 00:26:05.333
I bought... Not so long ago,
about three or four years ago,

00:26:05.367 --> 00:26:08.900
I bought an RS Touring,
which is the factory sunroof.

00:26:08.933 --> 00:26:10.833
-Yeah.
-Rear-seat 911, you know,

00:26:10.867 --> 00:26:14.067
-Carrera down the side,
wide arches, 2.7 engine.
-Yeah.

00:26:14.067 --> 00:26:16.300
Then I got a 911 GT3 RS,

00:26:16.333 --> 00:26:21.167
the reason being because
I thought this car is gonna
be a future classic...

00:26:21.200 --> 00:26:24.633
-At present at 997?
-A 997 GT 3RS, yeah.

00:26:24.667 --> 00:26:29.833
I've then subsequently
gone and got myself
a 911 RS lightweight.

00:26:29.867 --> 00:26:35.933
No, because I don't...
I still genuinely don't
get the appeal of 911s.

00:26:35.967 --> 00:26:39.133
-Right.
-Have you driven
a modern-day Turbo?

00:26:39.167 --> 00:26:41.067
Not for a while.
But I've driven an RS.

00:26:41.067 --> 00:26:42.200
-You know what I mean?
-Yeah, yeah. Sure.

00:26:42.233 --> 00:26:44.267
So you drive it...
Or even a GT3 RS.

00:26:44.300 --> 00:26:47.133
I drive that and think,
"Actually, this
is a nice car,"

00:26:47.167 --> 00:26:49.133
-I like it
but it's a nice car.
-Yeah.

00:26:49.167 --> 00:26:53.700
-Then I got into a GT2
the other day, the new GT2.
-Yeah, yeah. The Turbo, yeah.

00:26:53.733 --> 00:26:56.633
It's absolutely,
hideously horrid.

00:26:56.667 --> 00:26:58.633
-Oh. What don't you
like about it?
-And all...

00:26:58.667 --> 00:27:01.833
Well, it's because
it does everything
you expect a 911 to do.

00:27:01.867 --> 00:27:04.867
You get that bounce?
Do you know what I mean
by that front end bounce?

00:27:04.900 --> 00:27:06.333
-Yeah.
-And that understeer?

00:27:06.367 --> 00:27:08.200
If you do anything
about the understeer,

00:27:08.233 --> 00:27:11.500
they switch immediately
to death-dealing oversteer.

00:27:11.533 --> 00:27:14.067
JAY: Could it be you're not
driving it properly?

00:27:15.967 --> 00:27:18.167
-I turned the steering...
I turned the steering wheel!
-Could that be it?

00:27:18.200 --> 00:27:21.267
-I mean, that light weight
you've got...
-The air-cooled stuff, yeah.

00:27:21.300 --> 00:27:24.833
Yeah, the air-cooled one
is one day going to kill you.

00:27:24.867 --> 00:27:26.500
It's sitting
in your garage now

00:27:26.533 --> 00:27:28.633
-plotting how it's
going to do it.
-Yeah, yeah, yeah, yeah.

00:27:28.667 --> 00:27:30.733
Has anyone here got a 911?

00:27:30.767 --> 00:27:33.467
-See, they've all been killed.

00:27:33.500 --> 00:27:37.100
They were on their way
and they're all now
in a tree like that.

00:27:37.133 --> 00:27:39.767
-Honestly, I just
don't get them.
-Brilliant.

00:27:39.800 --> 00:27:43.067
-Um, there are a number
of other things.
-Yeah.

00:27:43.800 --> 00:27:46.067
He's got a Mercedes Grosser.

00:27:46.067 --> 00:27:48.200
Mine was owned by Coco Chanel.

00:27:48.233 --> 00:27:49.933
-It was actually
owned by Coco Chanel?
-Yeah.

00:27:49.967 --> 00:27:52.467
Your one, is it?
Mine was owned by
the Egyptian ambassador.

00:27:52.500 --> 00:27:57.833
Yeah, oh.
When I get in it,
I just cover myself in No.5.

00:27:59.400 --> 00:28:03.300
-And you've got a CSL BMW now.
-Tell us about the GQ awards.

00:28:03.333 --> 00:28:05.667
Oh, that's... Yes, well,
that's another thing
we've got in common,

00:28:05.700 --> 00:28:07.067
we've both won awards

00:28:07.100 --> 00:28:08.600
-from style.
-Yeah, you got
Worst Dressed Man,

00:28:08.633 --> 00:28:10.733
-and I got Style Man
of the Year.

00:28:10.767 --> 00:28:13.567
Mind you...

00:28:13.600 --> 00:28:16.833
Look, dear, I like them.

00:28:16.867 --> 00:28:19.200
What... Get off!
Show the people at the back.

00:28:19.233 --> 00:28:20.733
There's nothing
wrong with them!

00:28:20.767 --> 00:28:22.367
CLARKSON: Style of the year?

00:28:23.900 --> 00:28:26.333
-JAY: They're nice!
-It's not nice. It's hideous.

00:28:26.367 --> 00:28:29.400
Just because
Alpinestars don't
make you shoes.

00:28:29.433 --> 00:28:32.067
No, 'cause I go to a shoe shop
and say, "Have you
got a pair of shoes?"

00:28:32.067 --> 00:28:35.233
"Have you got a pair
of shoes for a hippo?"

00:28:37.800 --> 00:28:39.833
-Right now, listen, we've
talked about cars enough.
-Yeah.

00:28:39.867 --> 00:28:42.067
-Which is great
talking to you.
-Which is great! I love...

00:28:42.067 --> 00:28:44.400
-We do genuinely
share the same...
-We do share passions.

00:28:44.433 --> 00:28:46.300
Oh, we like the same motors.
We do like the same motors.

00:28:46.333 --> 00:28:49.767
It is...
Yeah. We do have
the same sort of cars.

00:28:49.800 --> 00:28:51.633
-Yeah.
-Right, the lap.

00:28:51.667 --> 00:28:55.500
-Yeah, oh.
-Now, see, when you
came the last time, old Stig.

00:28:55.533 --> 00:28:57.433
So, what's
the new Stig like now,
he's regenerated?

00:28:57.467 --> 00:28:59.100
Well, I have been out
with the new Stig

00:28:59.133 --> 00:29:01.667
-who is sort of,
in the master class, isn't he?
-Mmm-hmm.

00:29:01.700 --> 00:29:03.700
I've just been out
in that C63.

00:29:03.733 --> 00:29:06.167
-He is an extremely
good driver.
-Extraordinarily good driver!

00:29:06.200 --> 00:29:08.633
He is quicker than
Lewis Hamilton,
Nigel Mansell and Mark Webber.

00:29:08.667 --> 00:29:10.600
Yeah, and the funny thing is,
when you're talking to him...

00:29:10.633 --> 00:29:14.833
You know, we go outside,
we'd just had a bit of dinner,
and, uh, chatting away,

00:29:14.867 --> 00:29:17.800
and I said, "What are you
gonna have? Are you gonna
have the ribs and coleslaw?"

00:29:17.833 --> 00:29:20.100
And you suddenly find
you are talking to this guy
with this screen.

00:29:20.133 --> 00:29:21.667
-And then what happens,

00:29:21.700 --> 00:29:24.333
he lifts it up
for a bit of air,
you start doing that.

00:29:24.367 --> 00:29:27.300
-Trying to look
underneath at who it is

00:29:27.333 --> 00:29:29.067
and then he goes
and shuts it again.

00:29:29.100 --> 00:29:31.500
Well, he is filtering out
the carbon dioxide.

00:29:31.533 --> 00:29:33.333
-He runs on pure nitrogen.
-Yeah.

00:29:33.367 --> 00:29:36.133
-Anyway, he coached you?
-He did. He did.

00:29:36.167 --> 00:29:38.867
You had your nine laps.
And obviously,
there's no point

00:29:38.900 --> 00:29:41.367
-saying this week, where do
you think you've come?
-He did. He did. Oh!

00:29:41.400 --> 00:29:43.567
Because you want to be here,
don't you?

00:29:43.600 --> 00:29:47.933
I don't...
What can I say,
but yes, yes, yes!

00:29:49.500 --> 00:29:51.633
-More than the next Grammy?
-Yes!

00:29:51.667 --> 00:29:53.900
-Do you know...
I mean, do you know...

00:29:53.933 --> 00:29:56.600
Do you know... I mean,
do you know, people stop me
in the street and go,

00:29:56.633 --> 00:29:59.133
"When are you back
on  Top Gear? When are you
going to beat Simon Cowell."

00:29:59.167 --> 00:30:01.967
You know, they don't give
a  about the music!

00:30:04.733 --> 00:30:07.567
Get on with it then!
-No, no. Simon Cowell is...

00:30:10.367 --> 00:30:13.233
-That is what Simon Cowell
is doing at home now! No!
-No!

00:30:13.267 --> 00:30:14.900
-CLARKSON: Who wants
to see his lap?
-No.

00:30:14.933 --> 00:30:16.700
-AUDIENCE: Yes!
-The tape.

00:30:18.367 --> 00:30:19.567
CLARKSON:  All right.
Nice start.

00:30:19.600 --> 00:30:22.900
This is the one,
I must beat Mr Codpiece.

00:30:25.433 --> 00:30:27.200
CLARKSON:  Okay, now,
let's have a look
at that corner.

00:30:27.233 --> 00:30:30.400
-You see... No, it's...
-JAY:  Oh! Oh, it's scrubbing!

00:30:30.433 --> 00:30:34.267
-CLARKSON:  Scrubbing a bit
but not...

00:30:34.300 --> 00:30:36.000
CLARKSON:
Why were you angry?

00:30:36.033 --> 00:30:40.900
Because it is a gutless
piece of American
and I hate it!

00:30:40.933 --> 00:30:44.533
Oh, let's start shaving
little tiny, little bits
of Gordon Ramsay

00:30:44.567 --> 00:30:47.233
-parmesan cheese
off this .

00:30:47.267 --> 00:30:50.467
-CLARKSON:
There's Gordon Ramsay. He's...
-Go on, turn in, you pillock!

00:30:50.500 --> 00:30:52.367
-CLARKSON:  No, you're in,
you're in, just...

00:30:52.400 --> 00:30:54.267
-JAY:  Come on, come on,
come on, come on, come on!

00:30:54.300 --> 00:30:55.700
CLARKSON:  I'd have done
that tighter around
there personally.

00:30:55.733 --> 00:30:57.367
Come on! Come on! Come on!

00:30:57.400 --> 00:31:02.467
You really are a gutless bit
of Yankee...
Honestly.

00:31:02.500 --> 00:31:04.833
-CLARKSON:  You're cutting
that corner,

00:31:04.867 --> 00:31:06.867
we allow that
because it's slippery there.

00:31:08.800 --> 00:31:10.867
CLARKSON:
There is a man determined.

00:31:10.900 --> 00:31:12.633
JAY:  Now, go on,
get it in there!

00:31:12.667 --> 00:31:14.667
CLARKSON:  That is about
as good as I've ever seen

00:31:14.700 --> 00:31:18.867
-anyone doing the second
to last corner.
-JAY:   Get in there!

00:31:18.900 --> 00:31:20.867
-  Come on!
-AUDIENCE: Yes!

00:31:24.533 --> 00:31:25.967
Oh, no!

00:31:26.633 --> 00:31:29.233
Oh! I can't take it!

00:31:29.267 --> 00:31:32.233
Do you know,
I was sitting there yesterday,

00:31:32.267 --> 00:31:35.533
I thought,
"Top Gear tomorrow."

00:31:35.567 --> 00:31:38.367
I'm watching  The Right Stuff,
which I really enjoy,

00:31:38.400 --> 00:31:41.833
"Sod it, get to bed
and make sure you are
fresh as a daisy."

00:31:41.867 --> 00:31:43.433
What? You had an early night?

00:31:43.467 --> 00:31:45.067
I had an early night, yeah.

00:31:45.067 --> 00:31:46.567
So that you'd be capable
of doing this?

00:31:46.600 --> 00:31:48.067
So that I'd be capable
of doing this.

00:31:48.067 --> 00:31:49.767
-What I've got here...

00:31:49.800 --> 00:31:52.500
This is the piece of paper
just been given to me
by the producer

00:31:52.533 --> 00:31:53.867
with all your nine laps.

00:31:53.900 --> 00:31:55.700
It just isn't important,
this, is it?

00:31:55.733 --> 00:31:57.933
You know,
there's more important things
going on in the world!

00:31:57.967 --> 00:32:00.100
This is not important.

00:32:00.133 --> 00:32:01.667
-Right.
-It is important.

00:32:01.700 --> 00:32:04.200
So, your fastest lap
of the nine.

00:32:04.233 --> 00:32:05.567
Oh, Christ, what is it there?

00:32:05.600 --> 00:32:09.933
-What was he? 145.9.
-Nothing. 145.9.

00:32:09.967 --> 00:32:11.400
Come on, surely?

00:32:11.433 --> 00:32:13.533
Your fastest lap.

00:32:14.333 --> 00:32:15.867
One...

00:32:15.900 --> 00:32:17.467
I hate this.
I watch other people...

00:32:17.500 --> 00:32:19.567
I'm not supposed
to be doing this.

00:32:19.600 --> 00:32:21.200
-I used to watch
other people...
-40...

00:32:21.233 --> 00:32:23.167
JAY: Oh.

00:32:23.200 --> 00:32:25.767
-6.2...

00:32:27.467 --> 00:32:32.267
-...was your second...
Was your second fastest lap.

00:32:36.300 --> 00:32:39.300
-You...

00:32:39.967 --> 00:32:41.267
You...

00:32:45.700 --> 00:32:49.333
-Look, all I want to do...
-146.2 was your
second fastest.

00:32:49.367 --> 00:32:52.233
-Please let me...
-You did another 146.2.

00:32:52.267 --> 00:32:54.533
-148.2, too.
-Yeah, that was when...

00:32:54.567 --> 00:32:56.933
-149!

00:32:56.967 --> 00:32:58.600
Yeah, but that was
when I got the wrong gear.

00:32:58.633 --> 00:33:02.933
-147, 148.
And then on lap eight...
-Mmm.

00:33:02.967 --> 00:33:05.200
That'll be your quickest.
One...

00:33:05.233 --> 00:33:07.733
Well, you have 145.9 to beat.

00:33:07.767 --> 00:33:13.267
-145...
-I can't... Yeah.

00:33:13.300 --> 00:33:15.900
-...Point eight.

00:33:19.300 --> 00:33:22.800
-CLARKSON: You've done it.

00:33:30.067 --> 00:33:34.367
-Come on! Come on!

00:33:34.400 --> 00:33:36.267
Come on!

00:33:37.100 --> 00:33:39.667
Well, done, mate.

00:33:39.700 --> 00:33:43.300
Ladies and
gentlemen, Jay Kay.
The new number one!

00:33:50.533 --> 00:33:52.333
JAY: Thank you. Ah!

00:33:52.367 --> 00:33:54.833
It was a 145.81.

00:33:54.867 --> 00:33:57.067
You can take that home
and frame it.

00:33:57.100 --> 00:33:59.067
MAN IN AUDIENCE:
Who's the daddy?

00:33:59.100 --> 00:34:02.667
-Who's the daddy now?
-Not Simon Cowell.

00:34:02.700 --> 00:34:06.133
So we are back in the autumn
and the first guest,
I am guessing will be...

00:34:06.167 --> 00:34:08.100
-Simon Cowell!
-...Simon Cowell.

00:34:08.133 --> 00:34:09.467
-Brilliant!

00:34:09.500 --> 00:34:12.100
Ladies and gentlemen,
it has been a huge pleasure,

00:34:12.133 --> 00:34:13.767
-the new number one, Jay Kay!
-Thank you.

00:34:13.800 --> 00:34:16.333
-Thank you very much.

00:34:21.833 --> 00:34:25.733
Now, there's a new
TV show in Germany.

00:34:25.767 --> 00:34:28.833
It's all about cars
and it is hosted
by three people.

00:34:28.867 --> 00:34:31.067
I can't imagine
where they got
that idea from.

00:34:31.067 --> 00:34:33.233
-No.
-No idea.

00:34:33.267 --> 00:34:35.133
Anyway, they got
in touch with us

00:34:35.167 --> 00:34:40.633
and they invited us
to take them on in a series
of races and challenges.

00:34:40.667 --> 00:34:43.300
Now, obviously, we needed
somewhere to stage this.

00:34:43.333 --> 00:34:46.067
Yes, I suggested
we did it in the skies
over southern England.

00:34:47.367 --> 00:34:49.433
In fact, we settled
on Belgium,

00:34:49.467 --> 00:34:52.200
which was a country invented
so that Britain and Germany

00:34:52.233 --> 00:34:54.700
would have somewhere
to sort out their differences.

00:34:54.733 --> 00:34:58.067
Yeah, and on that point
the producers told us,

00:34:58.067 --> 00:35:00.167
"Now, listen,
you are representing
the BBC,

00:35:00.200 --> 00:35:03.533
"you can't just turn up
and go on about the war."

00:35:07.867 --> 00:35:09.867
CLARKSON:  The meet
was set for 9:00 a.m.

00:35:09.900 --> 00:35:13.967
for Belgium's second
best-known race track, Zolder.

00:35:17.667 --> 00:35:21.767
And at precisely 9:00 a.m.,
our Germans rivals arrived

00:35:21.800 --> 00:35:24.800
in their impressive
German cars.

00:35:33.600 --> 00:35:35.267
CLARKSON:
In fact,
we were not late,

00:35:35.300 --> 00:35:37.900
we were simply
arriving in style.

00:36:18.867 --> 00:36:21.833
CLARKSON: Come on, Biggles!
Come on out.

00:36:25.067 --> 00:36:27.133
We are on our own, we're...

00:36:27.167 --> 00:36:29.633
...playing for time
and it is running out!

00:36:42.700 --> 00:36:44.433
I think we might
have overdone this.

00:36:44.467 --> 00:36:48.400
It could be worse,
we could have come
in the back of Bobby Charlton!

00:36:48.433 --> 00:36:50.067
-Jeremy. Hi.
-How are you?

00:36:50.067 --> 00:36:52.233
Good to see you.
Good to see you.
How are you?

00:36:52.267 --> 00:36:53.933
CLARKSON:  Our small talk
was friendly,

00:36:53.967 --> 00:36:56.433
but, to be honest,
we were a bit nervous.

00:36:57.833 --> 00:37:00.500
Sure, they had
a jolly man in a suit.

00:37:00.533 --> 00:37:02.567
He is called
Carston von Ryssen,

00:37:02.600 --> 00:37:05.633
and he has
no racing experience at all,

00:37:05.667 --> 00:37:09.933
but then they also
have Tim Schrick,
the touring car driver

00:37:09.967 --> 00:37:14.400
and Sabine Schmitz,
the Nurburgring specialist.

00:37:16.667 --> 00:37:20.433
And they were up
against us lot.

00:37:20.467 --> 00:37:23.600
The first challenge
had been dreamed up
by the Germans.

00:37:23.633 --> 00:37:27.633
It's called
double-decker racing
and the idea is very simple.

00:37:27.667 --> 00:37:31.300
The car on the bottom
has a throttle,
brakes and gears

00:37:31.333 --> 00:37:32.633
but no steering wheel.

00:37:32.667 --> 00:37:36.600
Because that is fitted
to the car on top.

00:37:36.633 --> 00:37:39.933
Now, because there are
only three presenters
on each side

00:37:39.967 --> 00:37:43.333
and you need
eight people to operate
the four cars,

00:37:43.367 --> 00:37:47.500
each team is allowed
to get someone from
their film crew to help out.

00:37:47.533 --> 00:37:49.467
And that's a problem
for the Germans,

00:37:49.500 --> 00:37:52.900
because, while they
have a sound recordist,
a cameraman and a director,

00:37:52.933 --> 00:37:55.300
he is the same man.

00:37:55.333 --> 00:37:59.500
So, their coverage
of this race is going
to look like this.

00:38:00.933 --> 00:38:03.067
Mind you, but it's not
that brilliant for us,

00:38:03.067 --> 00:38:05.833
because, although we have
a very large film crew,

00:38:05.867 --> 00:38:08.733
uh, there was
only one volunteer
to sit above me

00:38:08.767 --> 00:38:13.067
and, if I am honest,
it is not the one
I would have picked.

00:38:13.067 --> 00:38:15.333
CLARKSON:  Still,
he is very brave.

00:38:15.367 --> 00:38:17.533
He once fought a shark.

00:38:17.567 --> 00:38:19.467
He lost, but anyway!

00:38:21.233 --> 00:38:25.133
We do six laps
and have six white stripes.

00:38:25.167 --> 00:38:27.767
-Okay.
-If you finish the first one,

00:38:27.800 --> 00:38:29.567
-you take one off.
-One.

00:38:29.600 --> 00:38:30.733
-James.
-MAY: Yeah?

00:38:30.767 --> 00:38:32.333
Will you promise
to use the throttle

00:38:32.367 --> 00:38:33.867
-and not just the brake?
-MAY: Yes.

00:38:34.900 --> 00:38:37.467
It's a bit odd
not having a steering wheel.

00:38:37.500 --> 00:38:39.800
These Metros always had
quite good steering,

00:38:39.833 --> 00:38:41.567
so this is a good way
round to do it.

00:38:41.600 --> 00:38:43.700
MAY: It doesn't make
a difference, you idiot!

00:38:43.733 --> 00:38:45.267
No the steering
is done by the Metro.

00:38:45.300 --> 00:38:47.067
No, but you're
steering the Jag.

00:38:47.067 --> 00:38:49.533
The good thing here is
they have Golfs on the roof.

00:38:49.567 --> 00:38:51.233
Now, Golfs are heavy.

00:38:51.267 --> 00:38:54.067
Metros are made
out of snake skin.

00:38:56.700 --> 00:38:59.167
CLARKSON:  Right.
Here we go.

00:39:01.533 --> 00:39:02.633
Yes!

00:39:02.667 --> 00:39:04.333
Oh, hang on, Jeremy.

00:39:06.967 --> 00:39:11.200
We have got
an early lead! Yes!

00:39:13.900 --> 00:39:16.067
We're already at the back!

00:39:21.433 --> 00:39:25.400
CLARKSON:  Jesus, that
is going to roll over
if we are not careful.

00:39:25.433 --> 00:39:29.467
At the end of lap one,
the German system
was working well.

00:39:32.333 --> 00:39:35.067
CLARKSON:  Whereas
in the Metro squadron...

00:39:35.067 --> 00:39:38.733
No! Look!
Look at what you are doing,
left, left, left!

00:39:38.767 --> 00:39:41.500
Left! Smooth!

00:39:42.933 --> 00:39:44.667
-CLARKSON: Right!

00:39:44.700 --> 00:39:47.333
CLARKSON:  Then there
was a complete
communication breakdown.

00:39:51.700 --> 00:39:53.233
Race cars...

00:39:54.733 --> 00:39:57.067
-Whoa!
-MAY: Whoa! Left, left, left!

00:39:57.100 --> 00:40:00.433
CLARKSON:  The Germans
were now first and second.

00:40:02.300 --> 00:40:04.600
-This is a disaster!

00:40:04.633 --> 00:40:08.233
CLARKSON:
Then there was another one.
My wing men went mad.

00:40:08.267 --> 00:40:13.500
-Stick on the inside.
-HAMMOND: Whoa!
No, no, no, no, no, no!

00:40:13.533 --> 00:40:16.800
-What the hell have
you done that for?
-MAY: What do you mean?

00:40:20.033 --> 00:40:23.733
-HAMMOND: That was your fault!
-How could it be my fault?
You're on the bloody steering!

00:40:23.767 --> 00:40:27.000
James and Richard
think it's all over,
and they're right!

00:40:28.067 --> 00:40:29.800
Rubbish! You steered
into the gravel.

00:40:29.833 --> 00:40:31.700
It is designed
to stop Formula One cars.

00:40:31.733 --> 00:40:35.600
How the hell
do you think a Jaguar
with a Metro on its roof...

00:40:37.000 --> 00:40:39.167
MAY:  This was
our darkest hour.

00:40:39.200 --> 00:40:41.933
-We are being annihilated!

00:40:41.967 --> 00:40:44.033
MAY:  With us out,
all we could hope

00:40:44.067 --> 00:40:47.833
was that Jeremy and Kiff,
the sound man, would race on
cleanly and fairly.

00:40:47.867 --> 00:40:50.667
-Ram him. Ram!

00:40:50.700 --> 00:40:52.600
Go, Kiff.

00:40:54.000 --> 00:40:56.733
Yes, they've gone wrong.
Kiff, we've got them!

00:40:56.767 --> 00:40:59.467
-CLARKSON:  Tim Schrick
was not just off,

00:40:59.500 --> 00:41:01.433
he was out.

00:41:03.400 --> 00:41:06.333
CLARKSON:  Now, it was just us
versus Sabine
and a man in a suit.

00:41:09.300 --> 00:41:12.533
Help yourself, Kiff.
There's no fighter escort.

00:41:15.133 --> 00:41:17.833
-Up the inside!
Baff! Yes!

00:41:19.167 --> 00:41:21.467
CLARKSON:  Go, Kiff.
They've gone down!

00:41:23.733 --> 00:41:25.600
-Onslaught!

00:41:29.867 --> 00:41:33.433
CLARKSON:
Keen to defend his country
and his job on Top Gear,

00:41:33.467 --> 00:41:35.067
Kiff made a bold move.

00:41:38.600 --> 00:41:40.400
CLARKSON:  That is giving them
something to think about.

00:41:40.433 --> 00:41:43.333
It also gave us
something to think about.

00:41:43.367 --> 00:41:46.267
KIFF: Whoa, Jeremy!
Jeremy, my arm's come off!

00:41:46.300 --> 00:41:49.133
-What?
-My arm's come off!

00:41:49.167 --> 00:41:52.967
Nobody
has ever said that
in a car race before!

00:41:55.900 --> 00:41:57.767
CLARKSON:
We were now on the last lap.

00:41:57.800 --> 00:42:00.633
Go up the inside,
Kiff with one arm!

00:42:09.600 --> 00:42:12.133
It is quite
difficult now, Jeremy.

00:42:16.133 --> 00:42:19.900
What... Oh, no,
it is the finish. No, no, no!

00:42:22.633 --> 00:42:27.067
I've let Britain down! Oh, no!

00:42:27.100 --> 00:42:32.067
CLARKSON:  Hopefully though,
we could redeem ourselves
in the next challenge.

00:42:35.267 --> 00:42:39.500
Who makes the fastest cars?
The axis powers or the allies?

00:42:39.533 --> 00:42:41.067
You came up
with this one,
didn't you?

00:42:41.067 --> 00:42:43.133
-Yes.
-And you haven't thought
it through, have you?

00:42:43.167 --> 00:42:45.700
Well, I did.
It is brilliantly simple.
It's just a drag race.

00:42:45.733 --> 00:42:47.367
Let's meet the contenders.

00:42:47.400 --> 00:42:51.500
On their side from Germany,
the highly modified
Porsche 9FF.

00:42:51.533 --> 00:42:54.067
From Italy,
the Lamborghini Murcielago.

00:42:54.067 --> 00:42:56.067
That's the LP640 version.

00:42:56.067 --> 00:43:01.067
From Japan, the Mitsubishi
Evo 10, that's the FQ-360.

00:43:01.067 --> 00:43:02.767
Yes, that's there's
and now ours.

00:43:02.800 --> 00:43:06.067
Our side from England
and driven by Wing Commander
Bunny Hammond,

00:43:06.067 --> 00:43:08.500
is the Ariel Atom,
the supercharged version.

00:43:08.533 --> 00:43:11.333
Then from America,
I was thinking
of you here, corporal,

00:43:11.367 --> 00:43:14.267
is the Callaway Corvette,
also supercharged.

00:43:14.300 --> 00:43:17.067
And like I was saying,
you haven't thought
it through, have you?

00:43:17.100 --> 00:43:19.367
-Well...
-Let me guess, James,

00:43:19.400 --> 00:43:22.133
New Zealand makes
a V16 rocket car

00:43:22.167 --> 00:43:25.400
-that somehow
we don't know about.
-They don't.

00:43:25.433 --> 00:43:27.700
MAY:  However,
India was on our side.

00:43:27.733 --> 00:43:30.800
So, whilst I waited
for one of their cars
to turn up,

00:43:30.833 --> 00:43:35.233
I sent the others off
to neuter the 250
mile per hour Porsche.

00:43:36.400 --> 00:43:38.400
And they decided
it would have trouble

00:43:38.433 --> 00:43:42.233
putting its 1000 horsepower
down off the line.

00:43:42.267 --> 00:43:46.133
So, what we need
is a really short race.

00:43:46.167 --> 00:43:47.667
If the race
is quarter of a mile,

00:43:47.700 --> 00:43:48.867
this is still
gonna be sitting here

00:43:48.900 --> 00:43:50.567
-spinning its wheels.
-Yeah.

00:43:50.600 --> 00:43:53.533
Right, you're gonna love this.
There are rules
and regulations.

00:43:53.567 --> 00:43:56.067
You like that sort of thing
concerning a drag race,

00:43:56.100 --> 00:43:57.900
and they are always
a quarter of a mile.

00:43:57.933 --> 00:43:59.667
-It's a standard...
-SABINE: No, no, no, no.

00:43:59.700 --> 00:44:03.833
-We drive kilometres.
At least one kilometre.
-One kilometre.

00:44:03.867 --> 00:44:06.200
HAMMOND: If you say
a quarter of a mile
everybody knows what that is

00:44:06.233 --> 00:44:07.667
-because it's
the standard measure.
-SABINE: No way.

00:44:07.700 --> 00:44:09.533
Half kilometre burger,
please... No.

00:44:09.567 --> 00:44:11.600
You don't.
It's a quarter pounder,

00:44:11.633 --> 00:44:13.900
and you have a quarter-mile
drag race.

00:44:13.933 --> 00:44:15.967
-It's the British way.
-HAMMOND: Let's do it.

00:44:17.367 --> 00:44:19.267
CLARKSON:  With the 9FF
hopefully out of it,

00:44:19.300 --> 00:44:21.833
my attention
turned to the Lamborghini.

00:44:24.100 --> 00:44:30.333
What I'm hoping,
praying is that being Italian
it changes sides halfway down.

00:44:30.367 --> 00:44:34.533
CLARKSON:  As we got ready,
James's Indian car
finally turned up.

00:44:34.567 --> 00:44:38.500
Supercharged. Supercharged.
Charged.

00:44:50.900 --> 00:44:54.200
James, don't forget
to turn your traction
control off, mate.

00:44:56.467 --> 00:45:01.667
Cock. I've just remembered
the Australians.
They do that VXR thing.

00:45:05.533 --> 00:45:08.167
CLARKSON:  Lofty Hammond
got a lightning start.

00:45:12.300 --> 00:45:14.800
This is unbelievable
acceleration!

00:45:16.900 --> 00:45:21.100
CLARKSON:  The atom in the Atom
would clearly win
but who would come second?

00:45:21.133 --> 00:45:23.100
-Come on!
-Come on!

00:45:26.467 --> 00:45:28.433
The Lambo's got me.

00:45:28.467 --> 00:45:31.700
CLARKSON:
But could I hold off
that monstrous Porsche?

00:45:34.167 --> 00:45:35.300
Yes!

00:45:38.267 --> 00:45:41.667
Yeah, that is ours!
That is ours!

00:45:46.067 --> 00:45:49.300
-So, how do you feel now?
-MAN: Yeah.

00:45:52.867 --> 00:45:55.733
So we were first.
Let's just say that again,

00:45:55.767 --> 00:45:58.433
-just to make it clear, first.
-First.

00:45:58.467 --> 00:46:00.933
-First. Third.
-First. First.

00:46:00.967 --> 00:46:02.533
And last.

00:46:02.567 --> 00:46:04.567
-Well, you say
"last" because...
-SABINE: Yes!

00:46:04.600 --> 00:46:06.967
There's a symmetry to that,
we had first and last,

00:46:07.067 --> 00:46:09.233
the two most significant
places in the drag race

00:46:09.267 --> 00:46:10.767
-are owned by us.
-SABINE: And the middle!

00:46:10.800 --> 00:46:12.233
We own the whole territory.

00:46:12.267 --> 00:46:16.067
You won the double deckers,
we've got some points back.

00:46:17.667 --> 00:46:20.800
MAY:  The drag race
marks the end
of the team challenges.

00:46:20.833 --> 00:46:23.567
From now on,
it would be one-on-one.

00:46:26.667 --> 00:46:28.900
Now for this event,
Germany will be represented

00:46:28.933 --> 00:46:32.067
by ring mistress,
racing driver, Sabine Schmitz.

00:46:32.067 --> 00:46:35.733
We will be represented
by that.

00:46:35.767 --> 00:46:38.933
Anyway, the cars...
Each team must bring
something small,

00:46:38.967 --> 00:46:41.100
reasonably priced
and from their own country.

00:46:41.133 --> 00:46:45.067
So we've come up with this.
It's a Mini Cooper S.

00:46:45.067 --> 00:46:47.067
Sabine, what have you got?

00:46:47.100 --> 00:46:49.767
-I've got that car.
-What, the Golf?

00:46:49.800 --> 00:46:52.567
No, the Mini Cooper,
of course!

00:46:52.600 --> 00:46:54.067
Weren't you listening?

00:46:54.100 --> 00:46:55.833
-It's German.
-We said
it's from your own country.

00:46:55.867 --> 00:46:58.067
CLARKSON: It's not German.
HAMMOND: It's a Mini.
It's still a Mini.

00:46:58.067 --> 00:47:00.067
-You can't get more British
than a Mini!

00:47:00.100 --> 00:47:02.067
-That is...
-It's...

00:47:02.067 --> 00:47:05.967
Alec Issigonis! Now, how much
more of a British name
is there than Issigonis?

00:47:06.067 --> 00:47:07.267
-In every...
-Apart from Patel?

00:47:07.300 --> 00:47:09.400
British, British,
British!

00:47:09.433 --> 00:47:14.067
Okay, so we're
in the same cars.
Just let them do it.

00:47:14.067 --> 00:47:18.933
HAMMOND:  So, the International
Small Car Challenge,
and it goes like this.

00:47:22.100 --> 00:47:24.500
Slalom through the Ming vases.

00:47:24.533 --> 00:47:27.233
Steering is so easy.

00:47:27.267 --> 00:47:31.400
HAMMOND:
Reverse into the garage
of priceless crockery.

00:47:31.433 --> 00:47:34.467
Then take a J turn penalty
which, amazingly...

00:47:34.500 --> 00:47:36.933
-...the German missed.

00:47:38.900 --> 00:47:40.867
-Next, drive a figure of eight

00:47:40.900 --> 00:47:45.067
while a member of the other
team shoots at you
from a paintball tank.

00:47:45.067 --> 00:47:46.800
-One point off for each hit,

00:47:46.833 --> 00:47:50.533
escape the arena
through a tunnel
we shall call Dick.

00:47:53.300 --> 00:47:54.967
Yeah!

00:47:55.067 --> 00:47:57.300
HAMMOND:  But then
it was Jeremy's turn.
Gut  luck.

00:47:57.333 --> 00:47:59.433
-CLARKSON: Here we go!

00:48:03.433 --> 00:48:04.867
So far not one hit!

00:48:08.733 --> 00:48:11.467
-That's the ticket.

00:48:12.867 --> 00:48:16.300
CLARKSON:  Still, things
could only get better.

00:48:16.333 --> 00:48:19.833
-Oh! I've scored myself.

00:48:19.867 --> 00:48:23.167
I only had the figure of eight
to redeem myself.

00:48:23.200 --> 00:48:26.067
-CLARKSON: Come on, handbrake.
-Fire!

00:48:28.067 --> 00:48:29.233
Fire!

00:48:29.267 --> 00:48:31.400
An awful lot of bullets
hitting me here.

00:48:31.433 --> 00:48:33.600
CLARKSON:  And no wonder.

00:48:33.633 --> 00:48:36.433
-HAMMOND: James!
What are you doing?
-Shooting at Jeremy.

00:48:36.467 --> 00:48:39.400
-Well, he's on our side!
-Yeah, but why wouldn't you?

00:48:39.433 --> 00:48:41.467
You're right! You would! Fire!

00:48:45.733 --> 00:48:47.167
Come on, through Dick!

00:48:49.067 --> 00:48:50.300
Yes!

00:48:50.333 --> 00:48:52.233
CLARKSON:
Even that went wrong.

00:48:55.133 --> 00:48:57.567
So, I was trailing on points.

00:48:57.600 --> 00:49:01.200
But I could win some
back in the final part
of the challenge,

00:49:01.233 --> 00:49:04.467
the head to head one lap race
around the Zolder circuit,

00:49:04.500 --> 00:49:07.800
the winner
would be the first one
to get their towel

00:49:07.833 --> 00:49:09.300
on the sunbed.

00:49:09.333 --> 00:49:11.167
A date with destiny.

00:49:15.300 --> 00:49:18.167
She's ahead by what
she'd call a metre.

00:49:20.700 --> 00:49:22.300
SABINE: Whoo!

00:49:27.967 --> 00:49:31.067
CLARKSON:
She's breaking early there,
I'm not going to do that.

00:49:31.067 --> 00:49:32.967
I dive down the inside.

00:49:33.800 --> 00:49:35.600
I'm in the lead!

00:49:37.067 --> 00:49:38.367
I'm not in the lead!

00:49:47.133 --> 00:49:50.933
CLARKSON:  The TV idiot
was trying everything
to get past.

00:50:00.833 --> 00:50:03.133
Come on! Jeremy!

00:50:03.167 --> 00:50:05.900
This really was a proper race.

00:50:07.433 --> 00:50:09.867
I'm not talking, this matters.

00:50:20.367 --> 00:50:24.900
HAMMOND: Jeremy,
let him get something right.
Oh!

00:50:24.933 --> 00:50:26.700
Oh! No! No! No!

00:50:26.733 --> 00:50:30.033
-They've got
to get up to the bridge.

00:50:34.767 --> 00:50:37.967
CLARKSON:
There's no possibility,
in this environment,

00:50:38.000 --> 00:50:40.167
-of beating a German.
-That was feeble.

00:50:40.200 --> 00:50:42.000
-And then you didn't...
-Sorry.

00:50:42.033 --> 00:50:47.033
-Were you shooting at me?
In that tank?
-He was, yes, he did that.

00:50:47.067 --> 00:50:51.000
HAMMOND:  After that debacle,
we were trailing
by nine points.

00:50:54.833 --> 00:50:56.900
But I was handling
the next challenge.

00:50:56.933 --> 00:51:00.100
And it was to be a shoot-out
in my kind of car.

00:51:00.133 --> 00:51:02.667
The incredible Bowler Nemesis.

00:51:02.700 --> 00:51:07.233
4.4-litre V8,
300 brake horse power,
naught to 60 in six seconds.

00:51:07.267 --> 00:51:10.733
Top speed, 130 miles an hour.
But, as always, with a Bowler,

00:51:10.767 --> 00:51:13.667
it can do that
anywhere on anything.

00:51:13.700 --> 00:51:17.567
And better still,
my opponent
would be the accountant.

00:51:17.600 --> 00:51:19.467
-Driven a Bowler before?
-No.

00:51:19.500 --> 00:51:23.133
Good. Good.
Well, um, they're terrifying.

00:51:23.167 --> 00:51:26.867
-Does he not do any racing?
-No, never,
he hasn't got a car.

00:51:26.900 --> 00:51:29.300
No. He has a licence,
that's it.

00:51:29.333 --> 00:51:33.633
One driver dislodged his lung
when he went too fast.
Yeah.

00:51:33.667 --> 00:51:36.700
But you'll be fine,
you'll enjoy this.
Good luck.

00:51:36.733 --> 00:51:40.867
It would be a five lap race
over a track
that was 60% Tarmac

00:51:40.900 --> 00:51:44.300
and, thanks to James,
60% gravel.

00:51:56.067 --> 00:51:58.367
We are off.
Come on, mighty Bowler.

00:52:04.100 --> 00:52:06.200
HAMMOND:  On Tarmac,
the accountant kept up,

00:52:06.233 --> 00:52:10.067
but once we hit the dirt,
he wouldn't see me for dust.

00:52:11.967 --> 00:52:13.900
Yes! More like it!

00:52:14.867 --> 00:52:17.100
Meanwhile, back at base...

00:52:17.133 --> 00:52:19.900
MAY:
Sit down, colonel.

00:52:19.933 --> 00:52:22.600
You're not interested
in these, are you?

00:52:22.633 --> 00:52:24.467
Do you know what?

00:52:24.500 --> 00:52:27.833
Your mind cannot comprehend
of how uninterested I am
in things like this.

00:52:31.667 --> 00:52:36.133
CLARKSON:  Back on track,
Hammond couldn't shake the man
in the suit off his tail.

00:52:36.167 --> 00:52:39.300
He was clearly
a worthy adversary.

00:52:40.367 --> 00:52:42.700
Keep your foot in Hammond,
be brave.

00:52:48.500 --> 00:52:51.933
CLARKSON:
A point Hammond proved,
moments later.

00:53:03.833 --> 00:53:07.900
If you don't get that going,
Hammond, for us,
the competition is over!

00:53:07.933 --> 00:53:10.200
That didn't go well, then.

00:53:10.233 --> 00:53:12.633
-HAMMOND:  This was a race
we had to win.

00:53:12.667 --> 00:53:14.833
But the VAT man
had a big lead.

00:53:14.867 --> 00:53:18.300
Oh, this... I'm going
to get grief for this, now,
this is not good.

00:53:18.333 --> 00:53:19.433
Cooler! Eight weeks!

00:53:24.067 --> 00:53:25.933
Where's the track gone? Oh!

00:53:29.100 --> 00:53:31.067
-CLARKSON: Is he gaining?
-He is gaining.

00:53:47.467 --> 00:53:51.733
HAMMOND:  On the last corner,
I decided to take him
on the outside.

00:53:51.767 --> 00:53:53.067
I can have him here!

00:53:58.700 --> 00:54:00.100
Yes!

00:54:00.967 --> 00:54:03.100
Yeah! Ah!

00:54:03.133 --> 00:54:05.267
-CLARKSON: Well done, then.
-Thank you!

00:54:05.300 --> 00:54:07.067
CLARKSON:  You know
what a bad loser is?

00:54:07.067 --> 00:54:10.067
Well, Hammond
is what's called a bad winner.

00:54:12.167 --> 00:54:13.100
Yes!

00:54:13.133 --> 00:54:15.633
-Oh! Oh!

00:54:15.667 --> 00:54:17.933
HAMMOND:
What do you think of that?

00:54:17.967 --> 00:54:20.367
Well, then, congratulate me,
then, I've won.

00:54:20.400 --> 00:54:22.733
Did you notice, I was first?

00:54:22.767 --> 00:54:24.733
CLARKSON:
After Hammond's modest win,

00:54:24.767 --> 00:54:27.100
we were trailing
by just four points

00:54:27.133 --> 00:54:30.267
as we went
into the last event.

00:54:30.300 --> 00:54:33.167
It's a two-lap race
of the Zolder circuit.

00:54:33.200 --> 00:54:36.400
And it's between
a Porsche 911,
a racing Porsche 911,

00:54:36.433 --> 00:54:41.067
which will be driven by
professional racing driver,
Tim Schrick.

00:54:41.067 --> 00:54:45.600
And he will be against
an Aston Martin DBRS9,

00:54:45.633 --> 00:54:48.633
which will be driven
by James May.

00:54:48.667 --> 00:54:50.500
Do we have to use James?

00:54:50.533 --> 00:54:52.067
Well, no, you did
the Bowler thing,

00:54:52.067 --> 00:54:53.767
I did the Mini thing,
it's his turn.

00:54:53.800 --> 00:54:56.067
But, he's going to lose,
badly.

00:54:56.100 --> 00:55:00.733
CLARKSON:  Happily, though,
I'd come up with a plan.

00:55:00.767 --> 00:55:04.067
-CLARKSON: You know
what I mean?
-Clever. Very clever.

00:55:08.567 --> 00:55:10.533
-It's James.
-Yeah, it's James,
he's come in for the race.

00:55:10.567 --> 00:55:12.333
-CLARKSON: He always...
-Roughly James' size...

00:55:12.367 --> 00:55:14.333
SABINE: He lost 30 kilos
in five minutes?

00:55:14.367 --> 00:55:16.900
Yeah, he always
dresses like this when
he drives a racing car.

00:55:16.933 --> 00:55:18.667
CLARKSON: James,
best of luck, mate.

00:55:18.700 --> 00:55:20.067
-James, good luck, mate.
-SABINE: And his hair?
Who cut his hair?

00:55:20.067 --> 00:55:21.433
-CLARKSON: Best of luck.
-Good luck.

00:55:21.467 --> 00:55:23.400
-CLARKSON: He's lost it.

00:55:23.433 --> 00:55:26.100
Don't disturb him when
he's focused and in the zone,
ready for a race.

00:55:26.133 --> 00:55:27.367
He's ice-cool.

00:55:27.400 --> 00:55:28.733
Well, this could work.

00:55:28.767 --> 00:55:30.500
-Could do.
-There's every chance.

00:55:32.067 --> 00:55:33.833
CLARKSON:
It would be a rolling start.

00:55:33.867 --> 00:55:36.133
Because we were
four points behind,

00:55:36.167 --> 00:55:38.533
James, who's now
warming his tyres up,

00:55:38.567 --> 00:55:42.267
had to set off four seconds
after the Porsche.

00:55:47.933 --> 00:55:49.967
The race was on.

00:55:51.833 --> 00:55:54.167
-Go, James!
-Go, James! Go!

00:56:01.333 --> 00:56:03.700
CLARKSON:  The simple fact
of the matter is this,

00:56:03.733 --> 00:56:07.333
our young man
had to shoot down
their young man

00:56:07.367 --> 00:56:10.067
at the rate
of two seconds a lap.

00:56:22.200 --> 00:56:27.333
If he does full throttle
on the straight, I'm sure
it's not Captain Slow.

00:56:27.367 --> 00:56:30.200
-I know...
- That's
his nickname, you know?

00:56:30.233 --> 00:56:32.900
It's like we call him "Lofty".
It's the opposite.

00:56:35.367 --> 00:56:37.233
CLARKSON:  Towards the end
of the first lap,

00:56:37.267 --> 00:56:40.533
James had closed the gap
to just one second.

00:56:53.067 --> 00:56:55.200
James was driving brilliantly,

00:56:55.233 --> 00:56:57.333
-but, then, disaster.

00:56:57.367 --> 00:57:02.100
He locked up, he lost ground,
and then he had the work
to do all over again.

00:57:07.133 --> 00:57:09.267
Happily, James is no quitter.

00:57:09.300 --> 00:57:13.400
And with half a lap to go,
he was right back
under the Porsche's wing.

00:57:19.933 --> 00:57:23.800
With just two corners to go,
he made his move.

00:57:26.067 --> 00:57:27.233
CLARKSON: I don't want to see!

00:57:27.267 --> 00:57:29.067
HAMMOND: I can hear them,
I can hear them both!

00:57:29.067 --> 00:57:32.133
-CLARKSON:  Which car
would appear first?

00:57:33.467 --> 00:57:34.833
Which one?

00:57:36.067 --> 00:57:40.367
-It's there!
-The Stig! James!

00:57:53.067 --> 00:57:57.400
James. Some say,
you saved our bacon.

00:57:57.433 --> 00:57:59.900
Others say I was
bound and gagged
in the locker room.

00:58:00.067 --> 00:58:01.600
-HAMMOND: Yes.

00:58:01.633 --> 00:58:05.300
And on that bombshell,
that bouncing bombshell,
it's now time to end.

00:58:05.333 --> 00:58:08.100
Uh, if you are a German
